{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_fontaine_ver01/data/sn87055779/00517016652/1927010201/0099.xml":{"full_text":"'^TrnrnTrfmTil\nnrr**\n-r&rrrrr r-r-\u2014< -nm/imM/\"nr/fri:f*fn*\nru:turf rw n\u2019t' tmtmnmf inn.mnnwnnunutnrnn\nBANNER YEAR SEEN\nBY DODGE CONCERN\nG.C. Miller Reports Increase\nIn Volume of Busi\nness for 1926.\nIncrease In the volume of business\nand in net profits for 1926 were re\nported by G. C. Miller, president of\nthe Dodge Manufacturing corpora\ntion in an interview Friday. Com\nmenting on the year\u2019s business and\non the prospects for 1927, Mr. Miller\nsaid:\n\"For the Dodge Manufacturing\ncorporation, the year 1926 has shown\na larae improvement over the last\nfew years, both in volume of busi\nness and in net profits. This increase\nhas not been achieved without ef\nfort. but is in, a large measure due\nto careful thought on the part of the\nexecutives of the corporation in im\nproving products and developing\nr.ew markets.\n\u201cThis year 1927 starts with a satis\nfactory volume of unfilled orders on\nhand and give promise, as far as\nwo can anticipate, of better business\nthan 1920. The year past and the\ncorning year have both been notable\nfor the evidence which they give that\n.business is being more and more\nconeentrated in strong hands. The\npast year has also shown that those\nmanufacturers who have been suc\ncessful, have adjusted their methods\nof distribution to keep pace with the\nmodern idea of small but well bal\nanced stocks In the hands of dealers\nwith a rapid turn-over. The year has\nalso demonstrated that buyers of in\ndustrial equipment, while purchasing\nfreely, are nevertheless, carefully\nscrutinizing their purchases with a\nview to determining that equipment\n\u25a0bought shall serve to the fullest ex\ntent the purpose for which it has\nbeen bought.\"\nPROSPECTS BRIGHT\nIN RUBBER MARKET\nA favorable report of the year'^s\nbusiness anti an optimistic outlook\nfor 1927 were announced by John J.\nMurphy, office manager of the Rub\nber Regenerating Company of Mish\nawaka, in an interview Friday.\nSpeaking of the company's business,\nMr. Murphy said:\n\"In volume of business and net\nprofils the year of 1 926 was equal\nto, if not greater, than any in the\nhistory of the Rubber Regenerating\nCompany of Mishawaka. Prospects\nof the rubber market point to an\neven greater year in 1927.\nJoseph Fncick, 47. of SI5 Short\nstreet was arrested at his residence\nFriday evening at 9:15 o\u2019clock on a\ncharge of possession and sale of in\ntoxicating liquor and public nuisance.\nShirley Mason in \u201cSweet Rosie\nI O\u2019Grady,\u201d at the Temple.\nTEMPLE\nWhen the Columbia cast assem\nbled to make the first scenes for\n\u201cSweet Rosie O\u2019Grady,\u201d Shirley\nMason, who has the title role, glee\nfully called them together.\n\u201cWho can sing the song\u2019\u201d she\nasked, gazing at them doubtfully.\n\"Indade, an\u2019 'tis me who can sing\nit with nivver a lost note,\u201d replied\nWilliam Conklin, falling in*o the\nbrogue of IVitrolman James Brady,\nwhose part he plays in the picture.\n\"Iss dat so?\u201d inquired A. Alyn\nWarren, who appears as Ben Sha\npiro, the lovable old Second Avenue\npawnbroker. \u201cVeil. I should hear\nit foist before I don\u2019t call you a\nliar, yes.\u201d\nConklin\u2019s baritone swung into the\nfamiliar melody and presently the\nwhole cast was singing and the\nwords came back as familiarly as\nthe jazz of a current Broadway hit\nthat struck the street last night.\n\u201cSweet Rosie O'Grady\u201d was based\non the song written by Maude Nu\ngent 20 years ago, when Rat Rooney\nwarbled its wistful story in Tony\nPastor\u2019s. The picture has been\nmade to follow closely the romance\n*of the story in the song and in di\nrecting it, Frank R. Strayer made\nparticular effort to reproduce the\ncostumes and the life of the period.\nThe picture opens a three day en\ngagement at the Temple theater to\nday. Cullen Landis, Lester Bernard,\nJackie Combs and 