Farm. A Mcr. Bank Bldg.\nMisli. IS'! or 1513-J.\n2tl\nlil'lit. F. MBHKIIAKT A SONS\n\"Mishawaka's oldest It alters\"\nWill sacriliee $1,100 equity in 4 room\nall modern home, paved street, balance\non contract $2.Sid. Payments $30 -per\nmonth. Will take good, used, closed\ncar for equity.\n5 rooms modern, fireplace, near High\nSchool Priced to sell.\nAlto VO! GOING TO IttTI.D?\nIf so, we have a real bargain in a\nvacant lot or. East Third St., located 3\nlots fro\u201d'. ear and bus line, size 30x128.\nAil Improvements in and paid. Price\n$!K\u2019d.\nFarmers A M rchants Bank Bldg.\nMish. 270 or Misli. 301.\n2tl\nEASY TERMS.\nNorth Side. Stanley St 4\nrooni bouse. Good condition. $30\ncash\nNear Lincoln Way West. Grand\nBlvd. 3-room house. Garage.\nBargain. Sot) cash\nS Union St. 3-rooni house. Gas,\ncity water, electricity aud fur\nnace. $100 rash.\nE. 10th St. Good 4-room house.\n$20 per month.\nNear Spring St. New bunga\nlow. Modern. $100 cash.\nE. Broadway. Attractive 4\nrootn bungalow All modern con\nveniences except hath tub. $200\ncash.\nHome St., near Lincoln Way.\n4 room house. Good condition\n$100 cash.\nCOLPAERT REALTY CORPORATION\n120-12$ Lincoln Way West.\n30t3\nNORTH SIDE. 0 room partly modern\nhouse. Corner lot. Pavement $300\ncash. Teb phone Mishawaka 11S1. 2t4\nS. MAIN ST. ti room strictly modern\nhouse. Like new. Garage. Excellent lo\ncation. Reasonable cash payment. Bal\nance like rent.\nEAST EN'Il. English type bungalow.\nThoroughly modern. 5 room and bath.\nPull basement. Attic. I*atge lot.\nPaved street. Studebaker St., near\nMishawaka Av. Libera.\u2019* terms. Col\npaert Realty Corporation. 120-12S Lin\ncoln way W. 2t4\n$1,100 EQUITY\u2014 $200 CASH\nWill sacrifice a $1,100 equitv in a 4\nroom. all-modern home in RMei Park\npaved street. Balance on c>niract.\n$2.S50 WiLl sell for $200 cash balance\npayable $30 per month. CAI I US AT\nONCE\nGEO. F EKERHART SONS\n\"Mishawaka's Oldest Realtors.\"\nFarmers Bank Bldg. Mish 270.\n2\u00aetl\nT\u00ab> b'lrlmngt'\u2014Heal Estate.\nFOR SALE OR TRADE 'or Mishawaka\nproperty very desirable corner Partagi\nAv., S B., now leasee for r\u00abao!in\nservice station, price $0,000.\nELMER GBJFF\nPhone Mish. 7a or 152. 124 W M.\u00bbn Av\n12U\nSOCIETY\nAnnouncement was made New\nYear\u2019s eve of the engagement of\nMiss Evelyn Tate, of Montrose, Calif.,\nand Beo McKinley, of this city. The\nwedding date has not yet been set,\nbut it will probably take place in\nJune.\nMiss Tate is a graduate nurse, and\nhas been connected with the staff of\nSt. Joseph\u2019s hospital here for nearly\na year.\nMr. McKinley is a son of Mrs.\nD. M. McKinley, 222 W. Broadway,\nand is vice president of the Inde\npendent Tank Bine of this city.\nThe Past Chief club of the Pythian\ncircle was entertained Thursday\nafternoon with a potluck luncheon\nparty in the home of Mrs. Scott\nEasterday, 109 S. Spring street.\nTwelve guests were seated at an\nattractive table decorated in yellow\nand white. After the luncheon gifts\nwere exchanged.\nAfter the exchange the regular\nroutine of business was transacted\nand the club decided tq send a check\nto the Vawter children, who re\ncently lost their parents in an acci\ndent.\nThe next meeting of the club will\nbe Jan. 27, in the home of Mrs.\nRobert Denton, 218 S. Bogan Street.\n\u25a0\u2014O\nA dinner dance party, honoring\nMias Suzanne de Borenzi, daughter\nof Mrs. Joseph de Borenzi, of South\nBend, was given Thursday evening\nby Mrs. M. V. Beiger, Bineolnway E.\nThe guests were seated at three\ntables attractively decorated with\nlew bowls of red roses and lighted\nby tapers in silver holders. A minia\nture Santa Claus stood at each place.\nDinner was served at G:30 o\u2019clock\nand, following the dinner, the guests\nenjoyed the evening dancing to\nmusic furnished by Claud Moran and\nbis orchestra.\nA reciprocity tea will be held by\nmembers of the music department of\nthe Mishawaka Woman\u2019s club Tues\nday afternoon in the home of Mrs\nI. K. Parks, 1124 E. Mishawaka\navenue.\nFor this occasion members of the\nBremen musical club will render the\nprogram. Mrs. Percy A. Baker is\nchairman of the music department.\n\u2014o\u2014\nThe junior department of the\nMishawaka Woman\u2019s club will hold\nits first meeting of the new year\nMonday evening in the Mishawaka\npublic library auditorium.\nAt this time the junior department\nof the South Bend Woman's club\nwill present the program, part of\nwhich will consist of vocal selections\nby Miss Katherine Gillis; cornet\nsolo by Virginia Roberts, accompani\ned by Miss Gladys Hummer. Miss\nKatherine Jackson will entertain\nwith piano selections.\nMiss Virginia Gilliland will read\nthe second act of the play written\nby members of the junior depart\nment. Refreshments will be served\nwith Miss Beatrice Richardson in\ncharge.\nMr. and Mrs. I. K. Parks, 1124 E.\nMishawaka avenue entertained with\na dinner party on New Year\u2019s day at\ntheir home. Guests present from out\nof the city were Miss Isabella Os\nborn. Baltimore, Mrs. Frank Silk\nwood Grover, Elkhart, and A. H.\nAnderson of South Bend.\nDinner was served at noon and the\ntables were decorated with cut\nflowers. The afternoon was spent\nsocially.\nMembers of the Dinner bridge\nclub were entertained Friday evening\nwith dinner at the Anna Magnuson\nTea room of South Bend. Covers\nwere placed for Mr. and Mrs. J. W.\nStart ing\nToday For\nThree Days.\nFirst Local\nShowing\n[home f Belter Picture a\nShows Today\nat 1:45-3:30\n5:15-7:00\nand 0 1\u2019. M.\nFast Feature\nat 9:30\nA pawnbroker with a heart, a\npolitician with a pull, a boy with\na blue hook rating, and a Cin\nderella of the sidewalks of New\nYork. That\u2019s the colorful and\ndramatic triangle that makes\nthe song of the century the\nIpliotopiuy 01 uie uour. luuu enjoy omi-iey iramuuuu\nfrom Bowery tomboy to society belle. You've sung the song, hum\nmed it ami whistled it for years, now see the picture.\no rn r\nHAL ROACH Pnssnts\n-CHARLEY CHASE\nH faBB\ntOBRAGE\nWith GLADYS Hum\nResolutions\nHave you firmly resolved to save\na reasonable part of your next year s\nearnings?\nA resolution to that effect would\nbe well worth while.\nAsk For a Money Barrel\nAt Our Savings Window\nA Oj paid or* Savings A Oj\njo Compounded Quarterly /0\nM/5HAWAKA TR VS T\n*\u00bb*SAV//vG5 Bank\nSCENE FROM \u201cGOING CROOKED\" AT THE TIVOLI\nKeller, Mr. and Mrs. Fred N. Smith,\nDr. and Mrs. H. J. Graham, Mr. and\nMrs. E. H. Ahara, Mr. and Mrs. Rob\nert Robertson and Miss Margaret\nRobertson of Toronto, Canada.\n\u2014o\u2014\nA watch party was enjoyed by\nmembers of the Home Grove drill\nteam in the home of Mrs. Harry\nKimble, 31G W. Sixth street. A mis\ncellaneous program was rendered in\ncluding readings entitled \u201cThoughts\nof the New Year,\u201d and \u201cMy Best\nFriend,\u201d by Mrs. Leonard Pyke;\nvocal solo, \u201cWhat I Learned at\nSchool,\u201d by Mrs. Edward Light;\nreading, \u201cTwo Cigarets,\u201d by Mrs.\nJohn Minegar; and a dialogue, \u201cThe\nOld Year Out and the New Year In,\u201d\nby Mrs. Chester Haynes and Mrs.\nPyke.\nA potluck supper was served and\nthe society will hold another party in\ntwo weeks in the home of Mrs.\nGrace Ravencroft, 916 E. MishaVva\nka avenue.\nA. F. Bradley, secretary of the\nChamber of Commerce, will appear\n\u2018before members of the Civics and\nPhilanthropy department Thursday\nafternoon at its regular session.\nHis subject will be \u201cPossibilities\nof Co-operation.\u201d Mrs. W. Eugene\nLutterworth will have charge of the\nmusical program.\n\u2014o\u2014\nThe department of American\nhomo of the Mishawaka Woman\u2019s\nclub will hold a meeting Thursday\nevening in the Mishawaka public\nlibrary. \u201cHandicraft in the Home\u201d\nwill be the subject for this session.\nThe class recently organized com\nposed of 35 will have its first lesson\non this occasion in charge of War\nren L. Hanson. Miss Cora Ney will\nhave basketry work on display.\nHonoring the birthday anniver\nsary of her son Warren L. Hanson,\njr., Mrs. \u201danson pleasantly enter\ntained with a party Friday after\nnoon. The guests entertained were:\nMrs. J. L. McKenna and infant son;\nMrs. Lewis Iking and son: Mrs.\nTesla Lundry and daughter; Mrs.\nRalph Vance and son. Mrs. Hardy\nStebbins and son, Hardy Wesley.\nCovers were laid for the guests at\nattractive tables centered with red\nroses. A birthday cake formed the\ncenter attraction.\n\u2014o\u2014\nPersonals\nMrs. C. L. Ostrander, 1202 Lin\ncolnway W., will leave Sunday morn\ning for Youngstown, O., to visit her\nson and family.\nSALESMEN'S SCHOOL TO\nBE HELD NEXT WEEK\nThe annual school for Mishawaka\nI,'ubber and Woolen Manufacturing\nCo. salesmen will convene at Mfch\nawak next week. Approximately\n200 salesmen will meet at the school\nand dinner which is held each year\nprior to the new year\u2019s selling cam\npaign.\nNew men and substitutes will hold\ntheir first meeting Monday morning\nand will be in session for three days.\nOn Thursday the new men will meet\nthose salesmen who have traveled\nfor the company perviously. The an\nnual dinner wil be held in the com\npany room Thursday evening.\n4 PER CENT INTEREST COM\nPOUNDED QUARTERLY\nFour per cent interest paid front\nJan. 1 on deposits made on or be\nfore Jan. 5. compounded quarterly.\nFirst Trust Savings bank, in same\nbuilding and under same manage\nment as First National bank. Com\nbined resources over $4,000,000.00.\nAdv.-lt4.\nLuther Larance, 49, tin S. Spring\nstreet was arrested Saturday on\ncharge of speeding.\nFLOWERS BY\nTELEGRAPH\nDistance means nothing\nwhen you wish to remember\nsomeone far away with flow\ners. Our connections with the\nFlorists Telegraph Delivery\nservice enable yo to place your\nI order right here in Mishawaka,\nand have flowers delivered\nany place in the United States\nwithin a short time afterward.\nEDGEWATER\nFLORAL PLACE\n209 North Cedar Street\nfl Phone Mish. 13\nLIKELY INDUSTRY j\nSLUMP TO INJURE\nSOUTH BUILDING\u2019\nLouisville Cotton King Ex\npects Moderate Business\nRecession Soon.\nBy PHILIP S. TULEY\nPresident Louisville Cotton Mills.\nCo., Louisville, Ivy.\n(Written Expressly for International\nNews Service).\nLOUISVILLE, Ky\u201e Jan. 1.\u2014We\nhave the feeling that business in\n1927, while perhaps not slowing\ndown to the point of distress, is not\nlikely to be as active as in 1926.\nPrimarily we believe this will 'be due\nto an inevitable, and we think also\na healthy reduction in the building\nprogram. We believe it has been\npushed too far, especially in the\nform of smaller dwellings financed\non mortgages. We fear there will\nbe a good deal of distress experi\nenced in this connection when pay\nments already undertaken cannot\nbe continued because of slowing\nFarmers Merchants State\nBank will pay interest, starting\n\u2022Tan. 1, on all deposits made on or\nbefore Jan. 5. Four per cent, in\nterest compounded quarterly.\nAdv.-2t3.\ndown in industry and reduction in\nwage distribution.\nWe fear also that the buyer\u2019s mar\nket, which has existed for the las\nseveral years, is not unlikely to be\nget unsafe latitude in extension of\nlonger terms. It seems to us that a\ntimely warning in this connection\nmay well be offered by those in au\nthority. If favors are to be granted,\nit should be through the avenue of\nprice reduction rather than exten\nsion of terms.\nWe feel also that words of warn\ning may likewise wisely be offered\nagainst extension of installment 'buy\ning. We think this is equally dan\ngerous with the practice of purchas\ning homes on the installment plan\nwith negligible initial payments.\nThe depression in the South, duo\nto the decline in cotton, cannot fail\nto have a dampening effect on busi\nness, especially those industries and\nmerchants dependent upon the\nSouthern market.\nWe believe that this is a period\nwhen conservatism and caution are\nhighly desirable and we sincerely\ntrust that there will be no effort to\nforce the hand of business and ex\npand production unduly and thus\nbring about over-production, con\nfusion and disaster.\nFarmers <Xr Merchants State\nRank will pay Interest, starting\nJan. 1. on all dejtosits made on or\nbefore Jan. 5. Four per rent, in\nterest compounded quarterly.\nAdv.-2t3.\nPhotographs will be taken at the\nrate of 400 a minute by' a new cam\nera, if it lives up to its inventor\u2019s\nclaims.\nmu\nTHRILLING!\nCHILLING!\nLAUGH PROVOKING\n\u201cMASTER CROOK\u201d\nMYSTERY DRAMA\nBESSIE LOVE\u2014\n\u2014LESLIE FENTON\na nd Bis Cast\nd you sec \u201cThe Bat\u201d? Don't Wt\nss this his\u2014new\u2014Fox pro- TJl\nction. You\u2019ll enjoy It\u2014front Iffc\nDid\nmiss\nAuction.\nstart to finish.\n\u201cA CLOSE CAM/\u2019\nAndy Gump Two l\u2019art\nFeature Comedy\n\u201cFelix Cat Rusts A Bubble\u201d\nKat Komcdy\nFox News\nMajor Kee\nTIVOLI TIPS\nMystery to Intrigue\u2014Suspense to\nthrill\u2014Romance to warm the\nheart Humor to bring the\nlauglis\u2014You\u2019ll find them all in\n\u201cGoing Crooked.\u201d Come early.\nSpecial nere Tomorrow and\nTuesday\u2014Popular Harry Carej\nin \u201cThe Texas Trail\u201d an Intense,\npulsating story of Western dar\ning and bravery.\n/WILLIAM FOX\n/*\\eseNrs\nI\nHUABL^HiiTFirPAPANY\nJANUARY SALES\nOne solid month devoted to the exploitation of special merchandise in the form of\n\u201cFeature Events.\"\nThese \u201cFeature Events\u201d are made possible by advantageous purchases and by group\ning certain regular lines for clearance purposes.\nEvery section of the store is alive with dominating values.\nBEGINNING TOMORROW WE FEATURE\nBEDDING\nat new low price levels\u2014\nSheets Sheets Sheets\nStandard qualities, fully bleached, free from dressing and well finished with tape edges.\nSize 63x90 Size 81x90 Size 81x99\n80c $1.00 $1.15\nOthers to $1.29 Others to $1.49 Others to $1.59\nOther Available Sizes Are 63x99, 72x90, 72x99\nSheeting\n\u20149-4 Width\n37c yd.\nA quality well known and\nof close, even texture. Pure\nly bleached, 